Solution. First, we rearrange the equation so that there are two fractions on each side.

$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{1}{a-x}-\frac{1}{b-x}-\frac{1}{c-x}+\frac{1}{d-x}=0 \\
\frac{1}{a-x}-\frac{1}{b-x}=\frac{1}{c-x}-\frac{1}{d-x}
\end{gathered}
$$

By bringing the fractions on each side to a common denominator, we obtain fractional expressions whose numerators no longer contain the unknown:

$$
\frac{b-a}{(a-x)(b-x)}=\frac{d-c}{(c-x)(d-x)}
$$

After multiplying by the denominators and rearranging to one side, it becomes immediately apparent that (due to $a+d \neq b+c$) we are looking for the zeros of a second-degree polynomial $P(x)$.

$$
\begin{gathered}
(b-a)(c-x)(d-x)=(d-c)(a-x)(b-x) \\
P(x)=(b-a)(c-x)(d-x)-(d-c)(a-x)(b-x)
\end{gathered}
$$

These zeros are also all the solutions of the original equation, since the values $a, b, c, d$ that are not in the domain of the original equation will not make $P(x)=0$. By substituting the individual values into the polynomial, we find that $P(b)>0$ and $P(c)<0$. For the interval $(b, c)$, we have $b-x<0, c-x>0, d-x>0$, so $(b-a)(c-x)(d-x)>0$, and also $d-c>0, a-x>0, b-x>0$, so $(d-c)(a-x)(b-x)<0$, thus $P(x)$ takes positive values in this interval, so there cannot be a root here. Similarly, by examining the interval $(c, d)$, we can see that $P(x)$ only takes negative values here, so there cannot be a root here either.

We know about $P(x)$ that it takes both positive and negative values, so we have established that it has two distinct roots. Since the other root cannot fall into $(b, c)$, $(a, b)$, or $(c, d)$, it is certain that it falls outside $(a, d)$.

